video_description: UH-HO! Back in November and early December much-loved TikTok personality Chris (Chris Olson) took a trip to Australia 'on a whim', and though the content wasn't disclosed as an ad it got my compliance spidey senses tingling: üá¶üá∫ The official Sydney account responded by video within a quick couple of hours to give itinerary suggestions (anyone who knows social understands how this hardly ever happens without at least days of planning) üá¶üá∫ The Australian TikTok awards were taking place just a couple of days later üá¶üá∫ He took part in an 'impulsive' seaplane ride where he was given a 'surprise destination' ticket with no destination (an air ticket is a legally binding contract of carriage, so to my understanding the destination must be specified) Neither of his two videos were disclosed to be ads. Two¬†WAtoday¬†articles have cited that¬†Tourism Australia¬†has "likely breached its ethical advertising obligations", with $90,000 being spent on three influencers for this campaign, "and your taxes paid for it". Why is this harmful? ‚ùóChris received many comments lamenting the affordability of this trip, such as, "must be nice to just be able to do something like this. I can't even afford the most basic of things. What a life you have!" and "I wish I could afford spontaneous trips lmao" ‚ùóThere were also comments questioning visas in what was repeatedly termed a 'spontaneous trip' ‚ùóChris's undisclosed advertisements saw 34.8 million views and 4.6m engagements - we don't know if he was paid additional fees over the $30k reported, regardless that's a huge number of consumers watching and engaging with the content without understanding it was paid for. The fact it's now publicly come out this trip was paid for is a huge erosion of creator (and brand) - audience trust. An execution such as this takes a huge amount of time, co-ordination of logistics, and manpower, and the repetition of spontaneity within the activation is, let's face it, a big lie. The fact this was a government and tax-funded campaign seems to amplify the seriousness of non-disclosure. Tourism Australia said they "directed content creators and advocates to ‚Äúinclude a tag indicating they were a ‚Äòguest of @Australia‚Äô or ‚Äòhosted by @Australia‚Äô". None of the three influencers (including Francis Bourgeois) disclosed this brand trip. All of the three influencers have worked on multiple commercial campaigns and would be clear of their advertising disclosure responsibilities. The media attention on this case is fascinating - consumers are becoming savvier (and more skeptical!) and lack of appropriate disclosure is no longer seen as a 'whoopsie!' moment. Both brands' and creators' responsibilities have never been clearer: will this signify a move towards better compliance? #addisclosure #chrisolsen #asa #accc #influencermarketing #megainfluencer

video_description: UH-HO! Back in November and early December much-loved TikTok personality Chris (Chris Olson) took a trip to Australia 'on a whim', and though the content wasn't disclosed as an ad it got my compliance spidey senses tingling: üá¶üá∫ The official Sydney account responded by video within a quick couple of hours to give itinerary suggestions (anyone who knows social understands how this hardly ever happens without at least days of planning) üá¶üá∫ The Australian TikTok awards were taking place just a couple of days later üá¶üá∫ He took part in an 'impulsive' seaplane ride where he was given a 'surprise destination' ticket with no destination (an air ticket is a legally binding contract of carriage, so to my understanding the destination must be specified) Neither of his two videos were disclosed to be ads. Two¬†WAtoday¬†articles have cited that¬†Tourism Australia¬†has "likely breached its ethical advertising obligations", with $90,000 being spent on three influencers for this campaign, "and your taxes paid for it". Why is this harmful? ‚ùóChris received many comments lamenting the affordability of this trip, such as, "must be nice to just be able to do something like this. I can't even afford the most basic of things. What a life you have!" and "I wish I could afford spontaneous trips lmao" ‚ùóThere were also comments questioning visas in what was repeatedly termed a 'spontaneous trip' ‚ùóChris's undisclosed advertisements saw 34.8 million views and 4.6m engagements - we don't know if he was paid additional fees over the $30k reported, regardless that's a huge number of consumers watching and engaging with the content without understanding it was paid for. The fact it's now publicly come out this trip was paid for is a huge erosion of creator (and brand) - audience trust. An execution such as this takes a huge amount of time, co-ordination of logistics, and manpower, and the repetition of spontaneity within the activation is, let's face it, a big lie. The fact this was a government and tax-funded campaign seems to amplify the seriousness of non-disclosure. Tourism Australia said they "directed content creators and advocates to ‚Äúinclude a tag indicating they were a ‚Äòguest of @Australia‚Äô or ‚Äòhosted by @Australia‚Äô". None of the three influencers (including Francis Bourgeois) disclosed this brand trip. All of the three influencers have worked on multiple commercial campaigns and would be clear of their advertising disclosure responsibilities. The media attention on this case is fascinating - consumers are becoming savvier (and more skeptical!) and lack of appropriate disclosure is no longer seen as a 'whoopsie!' moment. Both brands' and creators' responsibilities have never been clearer: will this signify a move towards better compliance? #addisclosure #chrisolsen #asa #accc #influencermarketing #megainfluencer

video_description: UH-HO! Back in November and early December much-loved TikTok personality Chris (Chris Olson) took a trip to Australia 'on a whim', and though the content wasn't disclosed as an ad it got my compliance spidey senses tingling: üá¶üá∫ The official Sydney account responded by video within a quick couple of hours to give itinerary suggestions (anyone who knows social understands how this hardly ever happens without at least days of planning) üá¶üá∫ The Australian TikTok awards were taking place just a couple of days later üá¶üá∫ He took part in an 'impulsive' seaplane ride where he was given a 'surprise destination' ticket with no destination (an air ticket is a legally binding contract of carriage, so to my understanding the destination must be specified) Neither of his two videos were disclosed to be ads. Two¬†WAtoday¬†articles have cited that¬†Tourism Australia¬†has "likely breached its ethical advertising obligations", with $90,000 being spent on three influencers for this campaign, "and your taxes paid for it". Why is this harmful? ‚ùóChris received many comments lamenting the affordability of this trip, such as, "must be nice to just be able to do something like this. I can't even afford the most basic of things. What a life you have!" and "I wish I could afford spontaneous trips lmao" ‚ùóThere were also comments questioning visas in what was repeatedly termed a 'spontaneous trip' ‚ùóChris's undisclosed advertisements saw 34.8 million views and 4.6m engagements - we don't know if he was paid additional fees over the $30k reported, regardless that's a huge number of consumers watching and engaging with the content without understanding it was paid for. The fact it's now publicly come out this trip was paid for is a huge erosion of creator (and brand) - audience trust. An execution such as this takes a huge amount of time, co-ordination of logistics, and manpower, and the repetition of spontaneity within the activation is, let's face it, a big lie. The fact this was a government and tax-funded campaign seems to amplify the seriousness of non-disclosure. Tourism Australia said they "directed content creators and advocates to ‚Äúinclude a tag indicating they were a ‚Äòguest of @Australia‚Äô or ‚Äòhosted by @Australia‚Äô". None of the three influencers (including Francis Bourgeois) disclosed this brand trip. All of the three influencers have worked on multiple commercial campaigns and would be clear of their advertising disclosure responsibilities. The media attention on this case is fascinating - consumers are becoming savvier (and more skeptical!) and lack of appropriate disclosure is no longer seen as a 'whoopsie!' moment. Both brands' and creators' responsibilities have never been clearer: will this signify a move towards better compliance? #addisclosure #chrisolsen #asa #accc #influencermarketing #megainfluencer
